Expensive for adequate/substandard food (Spanish bias)  I am a Spaniard (from Madrid) that has been in Boston for more or less a year so I will admit I am biased given that I am used to the quality and price range of Spain when it comes to its cuisine.  The atmosphere at Taberna de Haro was good, the staff nice and attentive, but the quality to price ratio of the food was quite low. First, I must point out that this is Boston and the restaurant is located in a nice area (next to Tatte and Whole Foods), so I understand that the food is not going to be cheap. However, for this very reason I expected good food, maybe not authentic, but at least enjoyable. Some of the tapas such as the sausage, octopus, croquetas and cheese were indeed enjoyable, or at least adequate. Something you could try at any average bar in Spain (although there the portions would be considerably bigger and the price lower).  However, the Spanish omelette (tortilla de patatas) was simply bad. The texture was right but the flavor unpleasant (burnt and salty). This is honestly one of the worst I have eaten (and as you can imagine I have eaten quite a lot of them, including ready to eat-frozen type). Given that it is a Spanish restaurant and that tortilla de patatas is a staple of our cuisine, I think this is quite a big mistake.  I will be most definitely not coming back. The quality and authenticity of the food served just does not match the price.

I was pleasantly surprised by the portion size (we ordered the braised rabbit to split, the sauce was amazing) as we did not have to eat any more the remainder of the night. Apparently they are known for their gin collection, so I ordered the day's special gin and tonic which was fantastic. Great cocktails. Menu items, like rabbit leg is DISGUSTING and cruel. GO VEGAN. Put kindness and peace on your plate.

I had the albóndigas; absolutely perfect! The meat was perfectly cooked, the potatoes were crisp and not braised with the beef (perfect), and the seasoning and sauce was just...again, perfection, and it takes a lot for me to say anything was great let alone PERFECT. Get it.  The atmosphere is very cozy, dark, candlelit, and fancy. They have a bar (which I ate at), and a great menu with something for everyone, even vegetarians.  The bad part is the price and portions. For the price you pay, I expected more food, but to be honest, I'm not complaining too much because it was excellent, but because of it, I won't come here too often. As an occasional taste bud boost, however, I'm in! Very authentic Spanish (Spain) food.

Food and drinks are really good, the black paella alone is worth the diner, service is a BIG issue, we were a group of 6 people, don't ask me why but apparently is a big issue to push table together at this place so they want allow us to seat all at the same table, so we booked two different tables for 3 people each. We arrive and NO ONE of our table was ready, actually all the table in the patio were full with people eating, they let us wait for almost half hours. THIS IS NOT ACCEPTABLE, if a client book a table you are supposed to have a table to sit him/her /they at the time of booking. They did not and they didn't apologize neither, they just looked at us and say "you have to wait 20 mins" like if we were a walk in clients. UNREAL. (FYI in the end we ended up be 5 so they squeezed  us on a 4 persons table, I don't want to imagine how long it would take to wait for both (RESERVED) tables) This is already enough for a 3 star review, but they did something worst, once that they has us sat (30min waiting with a a reservation and no apologize at all) we waited, I'm not kidding, other 20 min to get just water. tables booked for 8:30, let us set at 9, let us order and bring us water 9:20, 9:45 first plate on the table (finally), 10 first drink on the table (yes, I know, food before drink, basic mistake!!). They really have to work on the service, especially because all the food, the wine and drinks that we got were GREAT, it is a shame to ruin a nice dining experience with such a bad, disappointing service!!!

I had such wonderful memories this place, but visiting it a decade later, I was sadly underwhelmed. The garlic  shrimp were tiny and overcooked, the torta forgettably bland, the croquetas overly seasoned with some sort of nutmeg like seasoning that drowned out the pork flavor. I was so excited for a delicious trip down memory lane, only to leave say "I guess you can't go home after all" and no drive to ever come back. Such a bummer.

The place is nice despite smelling the oil burning and the noisy fan (which does not work apparently) from the kitchen.  The wine list is good but way overpriced. (4 to 6 mark up)  The service is average.  The food was really not good and too expensive for what it was. I tried a lot of very simple dishes and none of them were good. I just could not eat them and sent them back. The owner decided to remove a couple of them from the bill. It was pretty embarrassing for the brand new waitress to pick up the full plate as she was all smiley thinking that was normal and never ask a question. I understand we all deserve a chance and are beginner but a minimum of training is mandatory and common sense. Finally the ingredients were from the can and nothing was fresh. Even the Bravas with their mayo/hot sauce were not good.  We were very disappointed and I am strongly surprised by the comments I read below by the people who gave 5 stars.  Time to put some effort in the kitchen and offer a decent tapas restaurant.

Delicious: lentil soup w/ sausage and bacon, grilled Basque sausage w/ brandada (cod, oil, potatoes), pisto (eggplant, peppers, onions, poached egg, my favorite), and magret de pato (roasted duck breast, w/ a weak sherry vinegar reduction & bitter endive that do not enhance the dish). 11/2012: still very good, but patatas bravas were too vinegary.

I went to this restaurant by the first time with my wife to have dinner. The place is nice, the service was decent, but we really dislike the food. The dish that I ordered was overcooked and my wife's dish was also not good. Maybe what happened is that we experienced a bad day in the restaurant, but now we don't have a good impression about it. Based on that I have no plans to return or recommend.

I previously wrote that Taberna de Haro always disappointed me, however I just went back to try their Tuesday pig roast and it was wonderful. Also good was their eggplant tapas, their main salad, and some kind of fruit dessert. Some of their wines are very reasonable although they tried to steer me to the $65- wines. The staff is pleasant and helpful but the restaurant still has tables packed together and the noise level is fairly high.

Just went back to Taberna de Haro in their newly expanded space and really enjoyed it.  Truthfully, you'll never find that tapas here taste as good as those in Spain.  That being said, the Taberna comes close.  Favorites were the chorizo en sidra and the croquetas.  Plus, the sangria was delicious!

Extremely overpriced. Food is presented nicely but seems like they are using something I could pick up from shaws for 1/10th of the price and add tobasco sauce to. In addition they made us wait an hour longer than our reservation time and kept telling us "10 more minutes" every 15 minutes.

The food can be hit or miss although never bad. The best items I've had are any grilled seafood (octopus for sure). The 'feisty potatoes' were ok but more chewy than crispy although the spicy sauce was pretty good. Definitely not the best tapas in Boston - Toro tops my list for tapas although at least Taberna de Haro takes reserves!  The servers are efficient and friendly. All in all I would return for a nice tapas and a glass of wine.
